The leaders of the Group of Seven (G7) emphasize the importance of advanced Artificial Intelligence (AI) systems, such as foundation models and generative AI, in driving innovation and transformation. However, they also recognize the need to manage risks and protect individuals, society, and democratic values. To address these challenges, they advocate for inclusive governance of AI. The leaders welcome the Hiroshima Process International Guiding Principles and Code of Conduct for Organizations Developing Advanced AI Systems and call on organizations to commit to these guidelines. They instruct relevant ministers to expedite the development of the Hiroshima AI Process Comprehensive Policy Framework, in collaboration with the Global Partnership for Artificial Intelligence (GPAI) and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD). They also emphasize the importance of engaging multiple stakeholders, including governments, academia, civil society, and the private sector, both within and beyond the G7, to ensure the comprehensive development and advancement of the Hiroshima AI Process. The leaders believe that this collaborative effort will create an environment conducive to the design, development, deployment, and use of safe, secure, and trustworthy AI systems for the global common good, including in developing and emerging economies. They also express anticipation for the UK's AI Safety Summit in November.